Relationships between numeric columns¶

We know how to create a scatterplot to visualize the relationship between 2 numeric (continuous) columns in a DataFrame.

In [8]:
sns.relplot(data=penguins, x="flipper_length_mm", y="bill_depth_mm")

plt.show()

/Applications/anaconda3/envs/cmpinf2100/lib/python3.8/site-packages/seaborn/axisgrid.py:123: UserWarning: The figure layout has changed to tight
  self._figure.tight_layout(*args, **kwargs)

Color by a Cat or Non-Numeric column¶

We will include a third var in the scatterplot. The 3rd variable allows us to GROUP BY or CONDITION ON a grouping variable!!!

For example, let's color by the species variable.

In [9]:
sns.relplot(data=penguins, x="flipper_length_mm", y="bill_depth_mm", hue="species")

plt.show()

/Applications/anaconda3/envs/cmpinf2100/lib/python3.8/site-packages/seaborn/axisgrid.py:123: UserWarning: The figure layout has changed to tight
  self._figure.tight_layout(*args, **kwargs)

The default CAT or QUALITATIVE color palette is used above. We can change the palette.

In [11]:
sns.relplot(data=penguins, x="flipper_length_mm", y="bill_depth_mm", hue="species",
           palette="Accent")

plt.show()

/Applications/anaconda3/envs/cmpinf2100/lib/python3.8/site-packages/seaborn/axisgrid.py:123: UserWarning: The figure layout has changed to tight
  self._figure.tight_layout(*args, **kwargs)

Most CAT or QUALITATIVE color palettes have a LIMITED num of colors to choose from.

The benefit of the default color palette is that is can handle an enormous number of categories!

Color by NUMERIC column¶

We can color by a third NUMERIC or continuous variable in a scatterplot.

Sequential color palettes are good for distinguishing LOW to MEDIUM to HIGH values.

But, you can also distinguish being AWAY from the MID POINT!!! That's where DIVERGING color palettes are best!!!

In [27]:
sns.relplot(data=penguins, x="flipper_length_mm", y="bill_depth_mm", hue="body_mass_g",
           palette="icefire")

You can always include a cat variable as facets!!

You can use 4 vars, 3 can be numeric and 1 can be categorical.

In [29]:
sns.relplot(data=penguins, x="flipper_length_mm", y="bill_depth_mm", hue="body_mass_g", col="species",
           palette="coolwarm")

plt.show()

/Applications/anaconda3/envs/cmpinf2100/lib/python3.8/site-packages/seaborn/axisgrid.py:123: UserWarning: The figure layout has changed to tight
  self._figure.tight_layout(*args, **kwargs)

A second cat variable can be associated with row facets. This will give 5 variables.

In [30]:
sns.relplot(data=penguins, x="flipper_length_mm", y="bill_depth_mm", hue="body_mass_g", col="species", row="sex",
           palette="coolwarm")

plt.show()

/Applications/anaconda3/envs/cmpinf2100/lib/python3.8/site-packages/seaborn/axisgrid.py:123: UserWarning: The figure layout has changed to tight
  self._figure.tight_layout(*args, **kwargs)

We could even show 6 variables...if we include a 3rd cat variable as the marker shape.

Seaborn denotes the shape as the STYLE if we are associating the shape with a column in the DataFrame.

In [31]:
sns.relplot(data=penguins, x="flipper_length_mm", y="bill_depth_mm", hue="body_mass_g", col="species", row="island",
            style="sex",
           palette="coolwarm")

plt.show()

/Applications/anaconda3/envs/cmpinf2100/lib/python3.8/site-packages/seaborn/axisgrid.py:123: UserWarning: The figure layout has changed to tight
  self._figure.tight_layout(*args, **kwargs)

Background Theme or Style¶

By default the background is white without gridlines.

We can change the style using sns.set_style() function.

In [32]:
sns.set_style("dark")
In [33]:
sns.relplot(data=penguins, x="flipper_length_mm", y="bill_depth_mm", hue="body_mass_g")

plt.show()

/Applications/anaconda3/envs/cmpinf2100/lib/python3.8/site-packages/seaborn/axisgrid.py:123: UserWarning: The figure layout has changed to tight
  self._figure.tight_layout(*args, **kwargs)
In [34]:
sns.set_style("whitegrid")
In [35]:
sns.relplot(data=penguins, x="flipper_length_mm", y="bill_depth_mm", hue="body_mass_g")

plt.show()

  self._figure.tight_layout(*args, **kwargs)
